My mental and emotional bandwidth has been real small lately. Choosing to let this part in.

It’s only hump day and so far this week we have completed a super secret video game callback, an in house training video, a multi page tech narration, 14 auditions, a onesie ruining baby poop explosion, two pumpkin patch visits, and a bout of bronchitis. Please send caffeine. Or a babysitter and sedatives. Or both. Yeah, maybe both. Thanks.

Last night I dreamt of fire balls relentlessly falling from the sky, hot tails of flame streaming behind them. As I looked out the window and saw them land on an already scorched earth, one that resembled the surface of the sun, my six year old ran up to me, PJ clad with sweat beaded upon his lip, telling me he needed me. “Mama please come to bed.” And as he threw his arms around my thighs, I remembered images of Palestinian homes with beds squished up next to each other on the living room floor. Captions that read “we sleep together so that if we are bombed in the night, no one dies alone.” The memory startled me enough that I awoke and knew exactly that that is also what I needed to do, given the fact that flame might be about to descend upon us from above. I gathered my babies close to me, one on each side. Impossibly soft  skin touching. Their sweet little exhales brushing my face. I held them close enough that we all began to sweat, and then I held them some more. We awoke on Christmas morning intact, at least as far as I know (unless this too is some sort of visceral fever dream, one of the dying). And now I suppose we will eat breakfast and open stockings as though everything is normal. Normal, despite the whispering feeling endlessly circulating under my skin that it is not. It is not. 

Hug your babies. 

And free Palestine. ✊🏽
